Dip-a-what? Even the name “diphtheria” sounds confusing! With so many nasty bacterial infections and viruses out there, it’s hard for parents to keep track. You may not have heard of the illness known as diphtheria, or know that it’s important to vaccinate your child against this infection. We have gathered all you need to know about diphtheria, from signs and symptoms to prevention so you can safeguard your child. Diphtheria is a bacterial infection that lives in the mouth, throat and nose of an infected person. It can be spread by coughing or sneezing. Up to 40% to 50% of patients who don’t get treated can die. The diphtheria toxin can cause damage to your heart, affecting its ability to pump blood. It can also prevent your kidneys’ ability to clear waste. Diphtheria is more common in: The good news is yes, diphtheria can be prevented. Preventing this disease depends almost completely on giving the diphtheria / tetanus / pertussis vaccine to children and non-immunised adults. Click here to download your vaccination schedule for both the public and private sector. Also make sure that your own booster immunisations are current. Call your doctor immediately if anyone in your family shows any of the symptoms mentioned above. It’s important to remember, though, that most throat infections are not diphtheria, especially in countries that have routine immunisations against it.